  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a global consensus that money laundering is against the law. It is illegal in virtually every country.\n\nHere's why and how that consensus exists:\n\n*   **International Treaties and Conventions:** The United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988), the UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000), and the International Convention for the Suppression of the Financing of Terrorism (1999) all require signatory nations to criminalize money laundering. These are very widely ratified.\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** The FATF is an inter-governmental body that sets international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction. Its recommendations are the global standard and are implemented by most countries. Countries are assessed for their compliance, and non-compliant countries can face sanctions or be placed on \"grey lists\" or \"black lists\" which can damage their economies.\n*   **National Laws:** Almost all countries have enacted laws specifically targeting money laundering. These laws criminalize the act of concealing or disguising the proceeds of crime so that the proceeds appear legitimate. They also typically require financial institutions to report suspicious activity.\n*   **Criminal Justice Systems:** Courts around the world regularly prosecute and convict individuals and organizations for money laundering offenses.\n\n**Reasons for the Consensus:**\n\n*   **Combating Crime:** Money laundering allows criminals to profit from their illegal activities (drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, etc.) and reinvest in further crime. Criminalizing money laundering helps to disrupt these criminal enterprises.\n*   **Financial Stability:** Money laundering can destabilize financial systems by introducing illicit funds, undermining the integrity of financial institutions, and creating opportunities for corruption.\n*   **National Security:** Money laundering can be used to finance terrorism and other threats to national security.\n*   **Economic Harm:** Money laundering distorts markets, undermines fair competition, and can lead to economic instability.\n\nWhile the specific laws and enforcement mechanisms may vary from country to country, the fundamental principle that money laundering is illegal is universally accepted.\n",
